After a brief semantic and historical presentation, the article presents the 
main trials and systematic reviews on the tertiary prevention and care of 
cancers through physical activity. It gives the keys to understanding how, in 
forty years of research, interventions dedicated to prevent physical inactivity 
to reduce the risk of cancer have become as indispensable as adapted physical 
activity (APA) programs for care pathways. If the public health message "move 
more" with or without cancer remains true, the research encourages practitioners 
